# TypeScript Conventions

## Style

- Strict mode is on — no `any` unless absolutely necessary (prefer `unknown` + narrowing)
- Use explicit return types on exported functions
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when reassignment is required

## Error Handling

Always catch errors with context. Never swallow silently.

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
try {
  await processTranscript(id);
} catch (err) {
  log.error({ err, transcriptId: id }, "Failed to process transcript");
  throw new Error(`Transcript processing failed: ${id}`, { cause: err });
}

// ❌ Wrong
try {
  await processTranscript(id);
} catch (e) {}
```

## Logging

Use Pino child loggers with structured fields — never `console.log`.

```typescript
const log = logger.child({ service: "my-service" });
log.info({ taskId, status }, "Task updated");
log.error({ err, taskId }, "Failed to create Jira issue");
```

## Imports

- Use `@/` alias for all project imports (e.g., `@/lib/types`, `@/lib/supabase`)
- Group: external deps → `@/lib` → relative imports
- Use `import type` for type-only imports

## Patterns

- Validate external data at boundaries with Zod schemas
- Prefer `async/await` over raw promises
- Use discriminated unions for state machines (task status, transcript status)
- Keep functions focused — extract helpers for complex logic
